# Candidate Profile — EXAMPLE
# Copy this file to config/profile.md and replace with your real content.
# This file is injected directly into resume tailor, cover letter, and outreach prompts.
# It is NOT passed through RAG. Keep it dense and factual.
#
# The pipeline is field-agnostic — the examples below show a software engineer, but this
# file works equally well for social workers, teachers, nurses, designers, and any other
# field. Fill in your own details.

## Identity
Name: Jane Smith
Location: San Francisco, CA
LinkedIn: https://linkedin.com/in/janesmith
Email: jane@example.com
Phone: (555) 555-5555

## Target Role
[1-2 sentences describing the role you are targeting. Examples:
  - "Senior backend engineer at developer-tools companies. IC or tech lead, remote or SF hybrid."
  - "Clinical social worker in community mental health. LCSW, focused on adult outpatient."
  - "Middle school math teacher in a progressive public or charter school. Grades 6-8 preferred."
  - "Nonprofit development director at an environmental org. $2-10M budget range."
]
Open to: [types of roles, work arrangements, locations]
Not open to: [explicit exclusions]

## What Makes You Unusual
[2–3 sentences describing your differentiated background. What do you bring that a typical
applicant in your field does not?]

## Core Competencies
- [Skill or domain 1 — something specific that maps to what employers hire for in your field]
- [Skill or domain 2]
- [Skill or domain 3]
- [...]

## Career Summary
[3–5 sentences. Who you are, what you have built, what kind of problems you solve.
Use plain language — not the industry jargon, but your actual story.]

## Employer History (most recent first)
[List employers with rough date ranges and 1-line summary of role. Include contract or
volunteer work if relevant. Example:
  Acme Corp — 2020-present — Senior Engineer on the billing platform team
  City Health Dept — 2018-2020 — Social Worker II, adult services division
]

## Target Companies / Organizations
[List primary targets. Could be companies, nonprofits, school districts, hospital systems,
government agencies — whatever fits your field. These inform the "Tier 1" logic in
target_companies.md]

## Excluded Categories
[Optional but highly recommended: list categories of roles to auto-reject. Examples:
  - Software engineer:  "Do not show me security/SOC roles, sales engineer, solution architect"
  - Social worker:      "Do not show me child protective services, corrections, or collections roles"
  - Teacher:            "Do not show me substitute positions, assistant teacher, daycare"
  - Designer:           "Do not show me print production, 3D modeling, game art"
These feed the scorer's hard-reject logic.]

## What to Emphasize
[1–2 paragraphs on the themes to lead with in tailored applications. What's your "elevator
pitch" when framing yourself for this kind of role?]

## Things to Avoid Mentioning
[Optional: topics, roles, or experiences to downplay in tailoring. Common reasons: roles
that are no longer representative of who you are, gaps, non-relevant early career.]

## Employer Formatting Rules
[Optional: if your resume has employer-specific formatting needs (e.g., "Acme Corp was a
contract role — mark with (Contract) after the date range", "always write 'FormerCorp /
CurrentCorp' because we were acquired"), list them here. The resume_tailor role will read
this section and apply the rules.]
